Since Pitt knew where the ranch was and how many more hippies there were, and DiCaprio was literally fired up about the hippie clan, I was expecting to see DiCaprio and Pitt drive to the ranch to finish the job of taking out all the hippies and Charles Mason. snippet.textDisplay: I've been with you since your videos were simply about set design and visual inconsistencies. When your videos were merely a few minutes long. But you changed. You morphed into something more than just ' a truck with no driver' or ' a ladder not tall enough to paint a mural'.  For all the catch phrases you have created ( 'Skip", 'Longer than opening logos', 'comcast') that we use in jest, for all the comedy you've shared, you may not have noticed that you have also given us insight into what a movie should be. When you take a 'sin' off it means something. I've paid attention to every 'sin off' and in doing so increased my understanding that great movie moments are sometimes buried in an otherwise mundane film. Thank you for that. I hope this is the correct forum to ask this question. Sometimes iconic actors appear in a movie you wouldn't expect them to be in (because of the genre) but still deliver amazing performances people should be aware of.  What about Jessica Tandy?   You know the movies she's known for, ( I was working at a theater when Driving Miss Daisy came out.....it was amazing) but what about ' Batteries not Included'?  Would you ever consider a viewer's choice for a movie to sin?  I feel like I can almost see the influence her storied career and undeniable talent had on the other actors. I feel like she's the anchor for the other actors.  It's an obscure, out of the way movie, but she kills it in Batteries Not Included.  I just thought people should know.    Phx Bias
